{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":930,"text":"Every day we face issues like climate change"},{"time":4058,"text":"or the safety of vaccines"},{"time":5488,"text":"where we have to answer questions whose answers"},{"time":8528,"text":"rely heavily on scientific information."},{"time":11989,"text":"Scientists tell us that the world is warming."},{"time":14870,"text":"Scientists tell us that vaccines are safe."},{"time":17411,"text":"But how do we know if they are right?"},{"time":19465,"text":"Why should be believe the science?"},{"time":21429,"text":"The fact is, many of us actually\ndon't believe the science."},{"time":24898,"text":"Public opinion polls consistently show"},{"time":27074,"text":"that significant proportions of the American people"},{"time":30084,"text":"don't believe the climate is\nwarming due to human activities,"},{"time":33625,"text":"don't think that there is\nevolution by natural selection,"},{"time":36564,"text":"and aren't persuaded by the safety of vaccines."}]},{"cues":[{"time":40465,"text":"So why should we believe the science?"},{"time":44096,"text":"Well, scientists don't like talking about \nscience as a matter of belief."},{"time":47707,"text":"In fact, they would contrast science with faith,"},{"time":50294,"text":"and they would say belief is the domain of faith."},{"time":53260,"text":"And faith is a separate thing\napart and distinct from science."},{"time":57038,"text":"Indeed they would say religion is based on faith"},{"time":60190,"text":"or maybe the calculus of Pascal's wager."},{"time":63884,"text":"Blaise Pascal was a 17th-century mathematician"},{"time":66560,"text":"who tried to bring scientific\nreasoning to the question of"},{"time":69370,"text":"whether or not he should believe in God,"},{"time":71242,"text":"and his wager went like this:"},{"time":73846,"text":"Well, if God doesn't exist"},{"time":76395,"text":"but I decide to believe in him"},{"time":78420,"text":"nothing much is really lost."},{"time":80398,"text":"Maybe a few hours on Sunday."},{"time":82011,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":83004,"text":"But if he does exist and I don't believe in him,"},{"time":86385,"text":"then I'm in deep trouble."},{"time":88402,"text":"And so Pascal said, we'd better believe in God."},{"time":91438,"text":"Or as one of my college professors said,"},{"time":93610,"text":"\"He clutched for the handrail of faith.\""},{"time":95836,"text":"He made that leap of faith"},{"time":97772,"text":"leaving science and rationalism behind."}]},{"cues":[{"time":102296,"text":"Now the fact is though, for most of us,"},{"time":104992,"text":"most scientific claims are a leap of faith."},{"time":108126,"text":"We can't really judge scientific\nclaims for ourselves in most cases."},{"time":112511,"text":"And indeed this is actually\ntrue for most scientists as well"},{"time":115351,"text":"outside of their own specialties."},{"time":117681,"text":"So if you think about it, a geologist can't tell you"},{"time":120201,"text":"whether a vaccine is safe."},{"time":121951,"text":"Most chemists are not experts in evolutionary theory."},{"time":124951,"text":"A physicist cannot tell you,"},{"time":127210,"text":"despite the claims of some of them,"},{"time":128653,"text":"whether or not tobacco causes cancer."},{"time":132007,"text":"So, if even scientists themselves"},{"time":134457,"text":"have to make a leap of faith"},{"time":135733,"text":"outside their own fields,"},{"time":137655,"text":"then why do they accept the\nclaims of other scientists?"},{"time":141583,"text":"Why do they believe each other's claims?"},{"time":143881,"text":"And should we believe those claims?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":147171,"text":"So what I'd like to argue is yes, we should,"},{"time":149947,"text":"but not for the reason that most of us think."},{"time":152830,"text":"Most of us were taught in school\nthat the reason we should"},{"time":155160,"text":"believe in science is because of the scientific method."},{"time":158572,"text":"We were taught that scientists follow a method"},{"time":161488,"text":"and that this method guarantees"},{"time":163844,"text":"the truth of their claims."},{"time":165840,"text":"The method that most of us were taught in school,"},{"time":169260,"text":"we can call it the textbook method,"},{"time":170836,"text":"is the hypothetical deductive method."},{"time":173620,"text":"According to the standard\nmodel, the textbook model,"},{"time":176714,"text":"scientists develop hypotheses, they deduce"},{"time":179671,"text":"the consequences of those hypotheses,"},{"time":182131,"text":"and then they go out into the world and they say,"},{"time":183841,"text":"\"Okay, well are those consequences true?\""},{"time":186215,"text":"Can we observe them taking\nplace in the natural world?"},{"time":189548,"text":"And if they are true, then the scientists say,"},{"time":192148,"text":"\"Great, we know the hypothesis is correct.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":195004,"text":"So there are many famous examples in the history"},{"time":197183,"text":"of science of scientists doing exactly this."},{"time":200062,"text":"One of the most famous examples"},{"time":202120,"text":"comes from the work of Albert Einstein."},{"time":204333,"text":"When Einstein developed the\ntheory of general relativity,"},{"time":206855,"text":"one of the consequences of his theory"},{"time":209171,"text":"was that space-time wasn't just an empty void"},{"time":212010,"text":"but that it actually had a fabric."},{"time":213919,"text":"And that that fabric was bent"},{"time":215520,"text":"in the presence of massive objects like the sun."},{"time":218900,"text":"So if this theory were true then it meant that light"},{"time":221649,"text":"as it passed the sun"},{"time":223177,"text":"should actually be bent around it."},{"time":225345,"text":"That was a pretty startling prediction"},{"time":227745,"text":"and it took a few years before scientists"},{"time":229733,"text":"were able to test it"},{"time":231011,"text":"but they did test it in 1919,"},{"time":233521,"text":"and lo and behold it turned out to be true."},{"time":235971,"text":"Starlight actually does bend\nas it travels around the sun."},{"time":239129,"text":"This was a huge confirmation of the theory."},{"time":241623,"text":"It was considered proof of the truth"},{"time":243428,"text":"of this radical new idea,"},{"time":244740,"text":"and it was written up in many newspapers"},{"time":246592,"text":"around the globe."}]},{"cues":[{"time":249130,"text":"Now, sometimes this theory or this model"},{"time":251480,"text":"is referred to as the deductive-nomological model,"},{"time":254914,"text":"mainly because academics like \nto make things complicated."},{"time":258298,"text":"But also because in the ideal case, it's about laws."},{"time":263559,"text":"So nomological means having to do with laws."},{"time":266061,"text":"And in the ideal case, the hypothesis isn't just an idea:"},{"time":269485,"text":"ideally, it is a law of nature."},{"time":271811,"text":"Why does it matter that it is a law of nature?"},{"time":274098,"text":"Because if it is a law, it can't be broken."},{"time":276826,"text":"If it's a law then it will always be true"},{"time":278934,"text":"in all times and all places"},{"time":280178,"text":"no matter what the circumstances are."},{"time":282384,"text":"And all of you know of at least\none example of a famous law:"},{"time":285613,"text":"Einstein's famous equation, E=MC2,"},{"time":289368,"text":"which tells us what the relationship is"},{"time":291168,"text":"between energy and mass."},{"time":293361,"text":"And that relationship is true no matter what."}]},{"cues":[{"time":297361,"text":"Now, it turns out, though, that there \nare several problems with this model."},{"time":301010,"text":"The main problem is that it's wrong."},{"time":304645,"text":"It's just not true. (Laughter)"},{"time":308147,"text":"And I'm going to talk about\nthree reasons why it's wrong."},{"time":310870,"text":"So the first reason is a logical reason."},{"time":313549,"text":"It's the problem of the fallacy\nof affirming the consequent."},{"time":317065,"text":"So that's another fancy, academic way of saying"},{"time":319891,"text":"that false theories can make true predictions."},{"time":322561,"text":"So just because the prediction comes true"},{"time":324555,"text":"doesn't actually logically\nprove that the theory is correct."},{"time":327777,"text":"And I have a good example of that too, \nagain from the history of science."},{"time":331708,"text":"This is a picture of the Ptolemaic universe"},{"time":334403,"text":"with the Earth at the center of the universe"},{"time":336265,"text":"and the sun and the planets going around it."},{"time":338860,"text":"The Ptolemaic model was believed"},{"time":340890,"text":"by many very smart people for many centuries."},{"time":344143,"text":"Well, why?"},{"time":345879,"text":"Well the answer is because it made \nlots of predictions that came true."},{"time":349316,"text":"The Ptolemaic system enabled astronomers"},{"time":351332,"text":"to make accurate predictions\nof the motions of the planet,"},{"time":354082,"text":"in fact more accurate predictions at first"},{"time":356601,"text":"than the Copernican theory\nwhich we now would say is true."},{"time":360925,"text":"So that's one problem with the textbook model."},{"time":363907,"text":"A second problem is a practical problem,"},{"time":366303,"text":"and it's the problem of auxiliary hypotheses."},{"time":369538,"text":"Auxiliary hypotheses are assumptions"},{"time":372367,"text":"that scientists are making"},{"time":374146,"text":"that they may or may not even\nbe aware that they're making."},{"time":377189,"text":"So an important example of this"},{"time":379850,"text":"comes from the Copernican model,"},{"time":381945,"text":"which ultimately replaced the Ptolemaic system."},{"time":385137,"text":"So when Nicolaus Copernicus said,"},{"time":387177,"text":"actually the Earth is not the center of the universe,"},{"time":389827,"text":"the sun is the center of the solar system,"},{"time":391745,"text":"the Earth moves around the sun."},{"time":393127,"text":"Scientists said, well okay, Nicolaus, if that's true"},{"time":396855,"text":"we ought to be able to detect the motion"},{"time":398619,"text":"of the Earth around the sun."},{"time":400577,"text":"And so this slide here illustrates a concept"},{"time":402633,"text":"known as stellar parallax."},{"time":404441,"text":"And astronomers said, if the Earth is moving"},{"time":408263,"text":"and we look at a prominent star, let's say, Sirius --"},{"time":411463,"text":"well I know I'm in Manhattan\nso you guys can't see the stars,"},{"time":413877,"text":"but imagine you're out in the country, \nimagine you chose that rural life —"},{"time":417608,"text":"and we look at a star in December, we see that star"},{"time":420475,"text":"against the backdrop of distant stars."},{"time":423240,"text":"If we now make the same observation six months later"},{"time":426194,"text":"when the Earth has moved to this position in June,"},{"time":430006,"text":"we look at that same star and we \nsee it against a different backdrop."},{"time":434105,"text":"That difference, that angular\ndifference, is the stellar parallax."},{"time":438287,"text":"So this is a prediction that the Copernican model makes."},{"time":441150,"text":"Astronomers looked for the stellar parallax"},{"time":443711,"text":"and they found nothing, nothing at all."},{"time":448693,"text":"And many people argued that this proved \nthat the Copernican model was false."}]},{"cues":[{"time":452559,"text":"So what happened?"},{"time":454047,"text":"Well, in hindsight we can say \nthat astronomers were making"},{"time":456730,"text":"two auxiliary hypotheses, both of which"},{"time":459277,"text":"we would now say were incorrect."},{"time":461940,"text":"The first was an assumption \nabout the size of the Earth's orbit."},{"time":465575,"text":"Astronomers were assuming \nthat the Earth's orbit was large"},{"time":468611,"text":"relative to the distance to the stars."},{"time":470949,"text":"Today we would draw the picture more like this,"},{"time":473413,"text":"this comes from NASA,"},{"time":474760,"text":"and you see the Earth's orbit is actually quite small."},{"time":477183,"text":"In fact, it's actually much\nsmaller even than shown here."},{"time":480174,"text":"The stellar parallax therefore,"},{"time":481713,"text":"is very small and actually very hard to detect."}]},{"cues":[{"time":485297,"text":"And that leads to the second reason"},{"time":487271,"text":"why the prediction didn't work,"},{"time":489130,"text":"because scientists were also assuming"},{"time":491045,"text":"that the telescopes they had were sensitive enough"},{"time":494055,"text":"to detect the parallax."},{"time":495955,"text":"And that turned out not to be true."},{"time":497972,"text":"It wasn't until the 19th century"},{"time":500506,"text":"that scientists were able to detect"},{"time":502190,"text":"the stellar parallax."}]},{"cues":[{"time":503726,"text":"So, there's a third problem as well."},{"time":506372,"text":"The third problem is simply a factual problem,"},{"time":509150,"text":"that a lot of science doesn't fit the textbook model."},{"time":511966,"text":"A lot of science isn't deductive at all,"},{"time":514239,"text":"it's actually inductive."},{"time":516007,"text":"And by that we mean that scientists don't necessarily"},{"time":518523,"text":"start with theories and hypotheses,"},{"time":520754,"text":"often they just start with observations"},{"time":522623,"text":"of stuff going on in the world."},{"time":525032,"text":"And the most famous example\nof that is one of the most"},{"time":527602,"text":"famous scientists who ever lived, Charles Darwin."},{"time":530667,"text":"When Darwin went out as a young \nman on the voyage of the Beagle,"},{"time":533829,"text":"he didn't have a hypothesis, he didn't have a theory."},{"time":537441,"text":"He just knew that he wanted\nto have a career as a scientist"},{"time":540507,"text":"and he started to collect data."},{"time":542519,"text":"Mainly he knew that he hated medicine"},{"time":545249,"text":"because the sight of blood made him sick so"},{"time":547067,"text":"he had to have an alternative career path."},{"time":549335,"text":"So he started collecting data."},{"time":551469,"text":"And he collected many things, \nincluding his famous finches."},{"time":554635,"text":"When he collected these finches,\nhe threw them in a bag"},{"time":556845,"text":"and he had no idea what they meant."},{"time":559185,"text":"Many years later back in London,"},{"time":561472,"text":"Darwin looked at his data again and began"},{"time":563705,"text":"to develop an explanation,"},{"time":566153,"text":"and that explanation was the\ntheory of natural selection."}]},{"cues":[{"time":569451,"text":"Besides inductive science,"},{"time":571510,"text":"scientists also often participate in modeling."},{"time":574446,"text":"One of the things scientists want to do in life"},{"time":576782,"text":"is to explain the causes of things."},{"time":579050,"text":"And how do we do that?"},{"time":580568,"text":"Well, one way you can do it is to build a model"},{"time":582820,"text":"that tests an idea."}]},{"cues":[{"time":584562,"text":"So this is a picture of Henry Cadell,"},{"time":586493,"text":"who was a Scottish geologist in the 19th century."},{"time":589359,"text":"You can tell he's Scottish because he's wearing"},{"time":590792,"text":"a deerstalker cap and Wellington boots."},{"time":593180,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":595334,"text":"And Cadell wanted to answer the question,"},{"time":596900,"text":"how are mountains formed?"},{"time":598668,"text":"And one of the things he had observed"},{"time":600184,"text":"is that if you look at mountains\nlike the Appalachians,"},{"time":602758,"text":"you often find that the rocks in them"},{"time":604391,"text":"are folded,"},{"time":605860,"text":"and they're folded in a particular way,"},{"time":607506,"text":"which suggested to him"},{"time":608950,"text":"that they were actually being\ncompressed from the side."},{"time":611899,"text":"And this idea would later play a major role"},{"time":613987,"text":"in discussions of continental drift."},{"time":616410,"text":"So he built this model, this crazy contraption"},{"time":618916,"text":"with levers and wood, and here's his wheelbarrow,"},{"time":621068,"text":"buckets, a big sledgehammer."},{"time":623510,"text":"I don't know why he's got the Wellington boots."},{"time":625408,"text":"Maybe it's going to rain."},{"time":626985,"text":"And he created this physical model in order"},{"time":630070,"text":"to demonstrate that you could, in fact, create"},{"time":634035,"text":"patterns in rocks, or at least, in this case, in mud,"},{"time":636709,"text":"that looked a lot like mountains"},{"time":638935,"text":"if you compressed them from the side."},{"time":640777,"text":"So it was an argument about\nthe cause of mountains."}]},{"cues":[{"time":644405,"text":"Nowadays, most scientists prefer to work inside,"},{"time":647453,"text":"so they don't build physical models so much"},{"time":649880,"text":"as to make computer simulations."},{"time":652241,"text":"But a computer simulation is a kind of a model."},{"time":655080,"text":"It's a model that's made with mathematics,"},{"time":656943,"text":"and like the physical models of the 19th century,"},{"time":660176,"text":"it's very important for thinking about causes."},{"time":663954,"text":"So one of the big questions\nto do with climate change,"},{"time":666569,"text":"we have tremendous amounts of evidence"},{"time":668372,"text":"that the Earth is warming up."},{"time":670252,"text":"This slide here, the black line shows"},{"time":672716,"text":"the measurements that scientists have taken"},{"time":674836,"text":"for the last 150 years"},{"time":676799,"text":"showing that the Earth's temperature"},{"time":678209,"text":"has steadily increased,"},{"time":679843,"text":"and you can see in particular\nthat in the last 50 years"},{"time":682689,"text":"there's been this dramatic increase"},{"time":684453,"text":"of nearly one degree centigrade,"},{"time":686793,"text":"or almost two degrees Fahrenheit."}]},{"cues":[{"time":689168,"text":"So what, though, is driving that change?"},{"time":691605,"text":"How can we know what's causing"},{"time":693940,"text":"the observed warming?"},{"time":695456,"text":"Well, scientists can model it"},{"time":697170,"text":"using a computer simulation."},{"time":699538,"text":"So this diagram illustrates a computer simulation"},{"time":702330,"text":"that has looked at all the different factors"},{"time":704451,"text":"that we know can influence the Earth's climate,"},{"time":707056,"text":"so sulfate particles from air pollution,"},{"time":709808,"text":"volcanic dust from volcanic eruptions,"},{"time":712778,"text":"changes in solar radiation,"},{"time":715012,"text":"and, of course, greenhouse gases."},{"time":717390,"text":"And they asked the question,"},{"time":719208,"text":"what set of variables put into a model"},{"time":722904,"text":"will reproduce what we actually see in real life?"},{"time":725880,"text":"So here is the real life in black."},{"time":727900,"text":"Here's the model in this light gray,"},{"time":730180,"text":"and the answer is"},{"time":731740,"text":"a model that includes, it's the answer E on that SAT,"},{"time":736127,"text":"all of the above."},{"time":738268,"text":"The only way you can reproduce"},{"time":739774,"text":"the observed temperature measurements"},{"time":741602,"text":"is with all of these things put together,"},{"time":743580,"text":"including greenhouse gases,"},{"time":745719,"text":"and in particular you can see that the increase"},{"time":748270,"text":"in greenhouse gases tracks"},{"time":750154,"text":"this very dramatic increase in temperature"},{"time":752360,"text":"over the last 50 years."},{"time":753840,"text":"And so this is why climate scientists say"},{"time":756274,"text":"it's not just that we know that\nclimate change is happening,"},{"time":759382,"text":"we know that greenhouse gases are a major part"},{"time":762150,"text":"of the reason why."}]},{"cues":[{"time":764880,"text":"So now because there all these different things"},{"time":767268,"text":"that scientists do,"},{"time":768757,"text":"the philosopher Paul Feyerabend famously said,"},{"time":772243,"text":"\"The only principle in science"},{"time":773869,"text":"that doesn't inhibit progress is: anything goes.\""},{"time":777848,"text":"Now this quotation has often\nbeen taken out of context,"},{"time":780464,"text":"because Feyerabend was not actually saying"},{"time":782582,"text":"that in science anything goes."},{"time":784532,"text":"What he was saying was,"},{"time":785876,"text":"actually the full quotation is,"},{"time":787900,"text":"\"If you press me to say"},{"time":789990,"text":"what is the method of science,"},{"time":791636,"text":"I would have to say: anything goes.\""},{"time":795265,"text":"What he was trying to say"},{"time":796343,"text":"is that scientists do a lot of different things."},{"time":798910,"text":"Scientists are creative."}]},{"cues":[{"time":801218,"text":"But then this pushes the question back:"},{"time":803328,"text":"If scientists don't use a single method,"},{"time":806799,"text":"then how do they decide"},{"time":808698,"text":"what's right and what's wrong?"},{"time":810156,"text":"And who judges?"},{"time":812050,"text":"And the answer is, scientists judge,"},{"time":814130,"text":"and they judge by judging evidence."},{"time":817013,"text":"Scientists collect evidence in many different ways,"},{"time":820422,"text":"but however they collect it,"},{"time":822044,"text":"they have to subject it to scrutiny."},{"time":824621,"text":"And this led the sociologist Robert Merton"},{"time":827181,"text":"to focus on this question of how scientists"},{"time":829361,"text":"scrutinize data and evidence,"},{"time":831040,"text":"and he said they do it in a way he called"},{"time":833848,"text":"\"organized skepticism.\""},{"time":835767,"text":"And by that he meant it's organized"},{"time":837651,"text":"because they do it collectively,"},{"time":839129,"text":"they do it as a group,"},{"time":840758,"text":"and skepticism, because they do it from a position"},{"time":843574,"text":"of distrust."},{"time":845028,"text":"That is to say, the burden of proof"},{"time":846990,"text":"is on the person with a novel claim."},{"time":849471,"text":"And in this sense, science\nis intrinsically conservative."},{"time":852614,"text":"It's quite hard to persuade the scientific community"},{"time":855186,"text":"to say, \"Yes, we know something, this is true.\""},{"time":858897,"text":"So despite the popularity of the concept"},{"time":861393,"text":"of paradigm shifts,"},{"time":862990,"text":"what we find is that actually,"},{"time":864274,"text":"really major changes in scientific thinking"},{"time":867059,"text":"are relatively rare in the history of science."}]},{"cues":[{"time":870779,"text":"So finally that brings us to one more idea:"},{"time":874342,"text":"If scientists judge evidence collectively,"},{"time":878050,"text":"this has led historians to focus on the question"},{"time":880612,"text":"of consensus,"},{"time":882031,"text":"and to say that at the end of the day,"},{"time":883926,"text":"what science is,"},{"time":885860,"text":"what scientific knowledge is,"},{"time":887530,"text":"is the consensus of the scientific experts"},{"time":890909,"text":"who through this process of organized scrutiny,"},{"time":893063,"text":"collective scrutiny,"},{"time":895368,"text":"have judged the evidence"},{"time":896610,"text":"and come to a conclusion about it,"},{"time":899407,"text":"either yea or nay."}]},{"cues":[{"time":901884,"text":"So we can think of scientific knowledge"},{"time":903608,"text":"as a consensus of experts."},{"time":905660,"text":"We can also think of science as being"},{"time":907432,"text":"a kind of a jury,"},{"time":909010,"text":"except it's a very special kind of jury."},{"time":911524,"text":"It's not a jury of your peers,"},{"time":913628,"text":"it's a jury of geeks."},{"time":915524,"text":"It's a jury of men and women with Ph.D.s,"},{"time":919158,"text":"and unlike a conventional jury,"},{"time":921600,"text":"which has only two choices,"},{"time":923290,"text":"guilty or not guilty,"},{"time":925975,"text":"the scientific jury actually has a number of choices."},{"time":929376,"text":"Scientists can say yes, something's true."},{"time":932160,"text":"Scientists can say no, it's false."},{"time":934740,"text":"Or, they can say, well it might be true"},{"time":937280,"text":"but we need to work more\nand collect more evidence."},{"time":940324,"text":"Or, they can say it might be true,"},{"time":941940,"text":"but we don't know how to answer the question"},{"time":943640,"text":"and we're going to put it aside"},{"time":944950,"text":"and maybe we'll come back to it later."},{"time":947873,"text":"That's what scientists call \"intractable.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":951875,"text":"But this leads us to one final problem:"},{"time":954481,"text":"If science is what scientists say it is,"},{"time":957419,"text":"then isn't that just an appeal to authority?"},{"time":959960,"text":"And weren't we all taught in school"},{"time":961022,"text":"that the appeal to authority is a logical fallacy?"},{"time":964249,"text":"Well, here's the paradox of modern science,"},{"time":967281,"text":"the paradox of the conclusion I think historians"},{"time":969553,"text":"and philosophers and sociologists have come to,"},{"time":972154,"text":"that actually science is the appeal to authority,"},{"time":975655,"text":"but it's not the authority of the individual,"},{"time":979431,"text":"no matter how smart that individual is,"},{"time":981830,"text":"like Plato or Socrates or Einstein."},{"time":985695,"text":"It's the authority of the collective community."},{"time":988809,"text":"You can think of it is a kind of wisdom of the crowd,"},{"time":991795,"text":"but a very special kind of crowd."},{"time":995921,"text":"Science does appeal to authority,"},{"time":997811,"text":"but it's not based on any individual,"},{"time":999861,"text":"no matter how smart that individual may be."},{"time":1002447,"text":"It's based on the collective wisdom,"},{"time":1004198,"text":"the collective knowledge, the collective work,"},{"time":1006840,"text":"of all of the scientists who have worked"},{"time":1008738,"text":"on a particular problem."},{"time":1011455,"text":"Scientists have a kind of culture of collective distrust,"},{"time":1014251,"text":"this \"show me\" culture,"},{"time":1016451,"text":"illustrated by this nice woman here"},{"time":1018401,"text":"showing her colleagues her evidence."},{"time":1021483,"text":"Of course, these people don't\nreally look like scientists,"},{"time":1023340,"text":"because they're much too happy."},{"time":1025326,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":1029338,"text":"Okay, so that brings me to my final point."},{"time":1033660,"text":"Most of us get up in the morning."},{"time":1036308,"text":"Most of us trust our cars."},{"time":1037718,"text":"Well, see, now I'm thinking, I'm in Manhattan,"},{"time":1039260,"text":"this is a bad analogy,"},{"time":1040558,"text":"but most Americans who don't live in Manhattan"},{"time":1043382,"text":"get up in the morning and get in their cars"},{"time":1045120,"text":"and turn on that ignition, and their cars work,"},{"time":1047649,"text":"and they work incredibly well."},{"time":1049650,"text":"The modern automobile hardly ever breaks down."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1052365,"text":"So why is that? Why do cars work so well?"},{"time":1055148,"text":"It's not because of the genius of Henry Ford"},{"time":1057652,"text":"or Karl Benz or even Elon Musk."},{"time":1060743,"text":"It's because the modern automobile"},{"time":1062885,"text":"is the product of more than 100 years of work"},{"time":1067919,"text":"by hundreds and thousands"},{"time":1069509,"text":"and tens of thousands of people."},{"time":1070845,"text":"The modern automobile is the product"},{"time":1072956,"text":"of the collected work and wisdom and experience"},{"time":1075745,"text":"of every man and woman who has ever worked"},{"time":1078092,"text":"on a car,"},{"time":1079700,"text":"and the reliability of the technology is the result"},{"time":1082615,"text":"of that accumulated effort."},{"time":1085298,"text":"We benefit not just from the genius of Benz"},{"time":1088155,"text":"and Ford and Musk"},{"time":1089221,"text":"but from the collective intelligence and hard work"},{"time":1091989,"text":"of all of the people who have worked"},{"time":1094240,"text":"on the modern car."},{"time":1095910,"text":"And the same is true of science,"},{"time":1097960,"text":"only science is even older."},{"time":1100804,"text":"Our basis for trust in science is actually the same"},{"time":1103378,"text":"as our basis in trust in technology,"},{"time":1106052,"text":"and the same as our basis for trust in anything,"},{"time":1110039,"text":"namely, experience."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1112317,"text":"But it shouldn't be blind trust"},{"time":1114161,"text":"any more than we would have blind trust in anything."},{"time":1116921,"text":"Our trust in science, like science itself,"},{"time":1119762,"text":"should be based on evidence,"},{"time":1121675,"text":"and that means that scientists"},{"time":1123177,"text":"have to become better communicators."},{"time":1125225,"text":"They have to explain to us not just what they know"},{"time":1128112,"text":"but how they know it,"},{"time":1129840,"text":"and it means that we have\nto become better listeners."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1133730,"text":"Thank you very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1135149,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}